Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Chop the @Potatoes{3} lengthways into 1cm slices, then into 1cm thick chips (no
need to peel).

Pop the chips onto a lined #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @Oil{to taste}, season with @BBQ Rub{1%sachet}, @Salt{to taste} and
@Pepper{to taste} then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn
halfway through.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @Onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced).

Thinly slice the @Tomato{1}(thinly sliced).

Lay the @Irish Chicken Breast{320%grams} out on a #cutting board{}.

Place your hand flat on top of the chicken breast and use a sharp #knife{} to
carefully slice through horizontally to make two thin steaks.

Repeat with the other breast(s).

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

> TIP: Notice a stronger smell from your chicken? Don't worry, this is normal
> due to packaging we use to keep it fresh.

Place a large pan over medium heat with a drizzle of oil.

Once hot, lay the chicken into the pan and season with salt and pepper.

Fry until browned and cooked through, ~{3-6%minutes} each side.

> IMPORTANT: Chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once cooked, remove the pan from the heat and sprinkle over the @Grated Cheese{50%grams}.
Cover the pan with a #lid{} and allow the cheese to melt, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> TIP: Cook in batches if the pan is too crowded.

Pop the @Brioche Buns{2} into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

To assemble the burgers, spread a spoonful of @Aioli{1%sachet} over the cut side
of each bun.

Top the base bun with the cheesy chicken steak, sliced tomato and onion.

Drizzle over the @BBQ Sauce{2%sachets} and close with the top bun.

Serve with chips and any remaining aioli alongside.